An interesting new feature in C# 3.0 is that of automatic properties on objects - this allows us to define a get/set property and the creation of the underlying field is taken care off for us.
We can therefore create a class like this:
public class Foo { public string Bar { get; set; } } Now ignoring the fact that it’s terrible OO to write a class like that, one thing that we’ve been wondering is what’s the difference between doing the above and just creating a public field on Foo called Bar like so:

One of my favourite features of IntelliJ is that it tracks the item that you currently have open on your Solution Explorer.
I thought this wasn’t possible in Visual Studio and had resigned myself to trying to remember which project each file was in. Luckily for me a colleague pointed out that it is in fact possible but is just turned off by default.
Tools &gt; Options &gt; Projects and Solutions &gt; Check &#39;Track Active Item in Solution Explorer&#39;
